<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	Guided Lecture Notes worksheet: "What Is a Differential Equation?" + "Classification"
	Book sections (Exploring Differential Equations, geoff-cox/debookrs):
		c0-whats-a-de/sec-connection-to-alg-calc.ptx
		c0-whats-a-de/sec-de-defn.ptx
		c0-whats-a-de/sec-variables.ptx
		c0-whats-a-de/sec-terms-coeffs.ptx
		c1-classification/sec-order.ptx
		c1-classification/sec-linear-terms.ptx
		c1-classification/sec-linearity.ptx
	Old deck: source/notes/latex/ 01 intro-topics folder

	Guided-notes mechanisms (see CLAUDE.md §4):
	  * <fillin characters="N"/>  -> an in-prose blank shown in BOTH builds.
	    The answer NEVER lives inside the tag; it is revealed in a following
	    <commentary> block. One <commentary> collects the answers for a group
	    of blanks, in order.
	  * <commentary component="instructor">
	                              -> instructor-only block. In PreTeXt 2.43.1
	    (the pinned CLI) the old `commentary` stringparam is gone; visibility
	    is now controlled by the component/version mechanism: the block is kept
	    only when "instructor" appears in the publication file's
	    <source><version include="..."/>. The instructor target's publication
	    lists it; the student target's does not.
	  * <exercise> + <solution>   -> multi-step guided computations whose
	    solution hides on the student copy (exercise-worksheet solution="no")
	    and shows on the instructor copy (solution="yes").
	  * <example>                 -> read-along only; its solution shows in
	    BOTH builds, so it is reserved for illustrations with nothing hidden.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-intro-classification" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>What Is a Differential Equation? Naming Its Parts and Classifying It</title>

	<objectives>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				This worksheet is the in-class companion to the sections you have
				already read on Runestone. By the end of our meeting(s) you should be
				able to:
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<ul>
			<li><p><term>Identify</term> whether an equation is a differential equation, and name its dependent and independent variables.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Label</term> the terms, free term, and coefficients of a differential equation.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Determine</term> the order of a differential equation from its highest derivative.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Classify</term> individual terms as linear or nonlinear.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Decide</term> whether a whole differential equation is linear or nonlinear.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Apply</term> these labels to differential equations that model real systems.</p></li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 1 : What is a DE? Variables, terms, coefficients                 -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<page>
		<title>What Is a Differential Equation?</title>

		<p>
			In algebra you solved equations like <m>y - 3t = 5</m> for a
			<em>number</em> <m>y</m>. A differential equation asks a harder question:
			it hands you information about a function <em>and its derivatives</em> and
			asks you to find the whole <em>function</em>. For instance, isolating the
			derivative in <m>y' - 3t = 5</m> gives <m>y' = 5 + 3t</m>, and the job is
			to find a function whose derivative is <m>5 + 3t</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check: one paragraph of blanks, then ONE commentary. -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						A differential equation is an equation that involves one or more
						<fillin characters="12"/> of an unknown function.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						For an equation to be a differential equation it must contain both a
						derivative and an <fillin characters="12"/> sign.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						If the unknown function depends on a single variable the equation is
						an <fillin characters="4"/> (ordinary differential equation); if it
						depends on more than one variable it is a <fillin characters="4"/>
						(partial differential equation). In this course, <q>differential
						equation</q> always means <fillin characters="4"/>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<commentary component="instructor">
			<p>
				<term>Answers, in order:</term> (1) derivatives; (2) equals; (3) ODE,
				PDE, ODE. Watch for the two things every differential equation needs at
				once&#8212;a derivative <em>and</em> an equals sign; an expression like
				<m>y''' - 4y'</m> is not a differential equation
				because it has no equals sign.
			</p>
		</commentary>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-antideriv">
			<title>Your turn: back to calculus</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve the differential equation <m>y' = 5 + 3t</m> by finding a
					function <m>y</m> whose derivative is <m>5 + 3t</m>. Why is there more
					than one answer?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Antidifferentiate both sides: <m>y = 5t + \frac{3}{2}t^2 + C</m>. Every choice of
					the constant <m>C</m> gives a function whose derivative is
					<m>5 + 3t</m>, so a first-order differential equation has a whole
					<em>family</em> of solutions rather than a single one. This is the
					recurring theme of the course: solving a differential equation means
					recovering a function, and the arbitrary constant is the fingerprint of
					the integration we did to get there.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-variables">
			<title>Dependent vs. independent variables</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					For each differential equation, name the dependent variable (the
					unknown function we solve for) and the independent variable (the one it
					is differentiated with respect to):
					<me>
						\frac{dW}{dz} + \frac{W}{z} = 9z^2, \qquad
						g'' + s^3 g = 0, \qquad
						R''' = 6R.
					</me>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The derivative tells you which variable is which&#8212;the dependent
					variable is the one being differentiated.
					<ul marker="square">
						<li><p><m>dW/dz</m> means <m>W</m> changes as <m>z</m> changes: dependent <m>W</m>, independent <m>z</m>.</p></li>
						<li><p><m>g''</m> is a derivative of <m>g</m> with respect to <m>s</m>: dependent <m>g</m>, independent <m>s</m>.</p></li>
						<li><p><m>R'''</m> shows <m>R</m> is the dependent variable; no independent variable is named, so you may call it whatever you like (say <m>t</m>).</p></li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p>
			<term>Vocabulary for the parts of an equation.</term> Before we can
			classify equations we need names for their pieces. Fill in the blanks.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						A <term>term</term> is any piece of a differential equation separated
						from the others by <fillin characters="18"/> signs.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						A <term>free term</term> is a term that does <em>not</em> involve the
						<fillin characters="10"/> variable or its derivatives. Every equation
						has one, even a hidden <m><fillin characters="2"/></m>: for example
						<m>w' = 4w</m> is really <m>w' - 4w = 0</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						A <term>coefficient</term> is a constant or a function of the
						<fillin characters="12"/> variable that multiplies the dependent
						variable or one of its derivatives.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<commentary component="instructor">
			<p>
				<term>Answers, in order:</term> (1) plus or minus (addition or
				subtraction); (2) dependent, and the hidden free term is <m>0</m>;
				(3) independent. A useful mantra: a free term is <em>free of the
				dependent variable</em>, and a coefficient may never contain the
				dependent variable.
			</p>
		</commentary>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-terms-coeffs">
			<title>Terms, free term, and coefficients</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The dependent variable below is <m>u</m>:
					<me>
						\frac{5}{t}\,u^{(4)} + 2.7\,u'' + t^3 u' + u = \tfrac14 e^{2t}.
					</me>
					(a) List the five terms. (b) Which is the free term? (c) Give the
					coefficient of <m>u^{(4)}</m>, of <m>u''</m>, of <m>u'</m>, and of
					<m>u</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) The terms are <m>\frac{5}{t}u^{(4)}</m>, <m>2.7\,u''</m>,
					<m>t^3 u'</m>, <m>u</m>, and <m>\frac14 e^{2t}</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) The free term is <m>\frac14 e^{2t}</m>: it contains the independent
					variable <m>t</m> but none of <m>u</m> or its derivatives. (Notice a
					free term need not be constant&#8212;this is why <q>constant term</q> is
					a misleading name.)
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) Reading off the multipliers of the dependent variable and its
					derivatives: coefficient of <m>u^{(4)}</m> is <m>\frac{5}{t}</m>, of
					<m>u''</m> is <m>2.7</m>, of <m>u'</m> is <m>t^3</m>, and of <m>u</m> is
					<m>1</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 2 : Classification (order and linearity)                         -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<page>
		<title>Classifying a Differential Equation: Order and Linearity</title>

		<p>
			Once we can name the parts of an equation, two labels let us predict which
			solution methods will work: its <term>order</term> and whether it is
			<term>linear</term>. We build both up on this page.
		</p>

		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						The <term>order</term> of a differential equation is the
						<fillin characters="12"/> derivative of the dependent variable that
						appears in it.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						A single term is <term>linear</term> if it has one of the forms
						<m>a(t)</m>, <m>a(t)\,y</m>, or <m>a(t)\,y^{(n)}</m>, where the
						coefficient <m>a(t)</m> depends on the <fillin characters="12"/>
						variable only. The coefficient <fillin characters="12"/> (does / does
						not) affect linearity, no matter how complicated it looks.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						A whole differential equation is linear when <fillin characters="8"/>
						term is linear; it is nonlinear as soon as <fillin characters="12"/>
						term is nonlinear.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<commentary component="instructor">
			<p>
				<term>Answers, in order:</term> (1) highest; (2) independent, does not;
				(3) every, one (a single). The headline for linearity: one nonlinear
				term is enough to make the entire equation nonlinear&#8212;linearity is
				an all-or-nothing property of the equation.
			</p>
		</commentary>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-order">
			<title>Reading off the order</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Give the order of each equation:
					<me>
						\frac{d^3 B}{ds^3} + \frac{dB}{ds} + B = 42, \qquad
						v^8 + \cos\!\big(v^{(6)}\big) = 0.
					</me>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The first is <term>third-order</term>: the highest derivative of
					<m>B</m> is <m>d^3B/ds^3</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					The second is <term>sixth-order</term>. Do not confuse the exponent in
					<m>v^8</m> (that is <m>v</m> raised to the eighth power, not an eighth
					derivative) with a derivative; only derivatives set the order. And the
					<m>\cos(\cdot)</m> wrapper does not change the order&#8212;the highest
					derivative inside is still <m>v^{(6)}</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-linear-terms">
			<title>Term-by-term: linear or nonlinear?</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Take <m>y</m> as the dependent variable and <m>t</m> as the
					independent variable. Label each term of
					<me>
						y'\,\frac{d^3 y}{dt^3} + 5t^4\,\frac{dy}{dt}
						+ \cos(y) + (y'')^2 = \sqrt{t}
					</me>
					as linear or nonlinear, and say which rule it breaks.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<ul marker="square">
						<li><p><m>y'\,\dfrac{d^3y}{dt^3}</m>: <em>nonlinear</em>&#8212;two derivatives of the dependent variable are multiplied together.</p></li>
						<li><p><m>5t^4\,\dfrac{dy}{dt}</m>: <em>linear</em>&#8212;it has the form <m>a(t)\,y'</m>; the messy coefficient <m>5t^4</m> is irrelevant.</p></li>
						<li><p><m>\cos(y)</m>: <em>nonlinear</em>&#8212;the dependent variable sits inside a nonlinear function.</p></li>
						<li><p><m>(y'')^2</m>: <em>nonlinear</em>&#8212;a derivative is raised to a power other than one.</p></li>
						<li><p><m>\sqrt{t}</m>: <em>linear</em> (in fact a free term)&#8212;no dependent variable appears.</p></li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-linearity">
			<title>Is the whole equation linear?</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Decide whether each equation is linear or nonlinear, and justify with
					one sentence:
					<me>
						w^{(4)} + \frac{w'}{t^3} + 9w = \tan t, \qquad
						Q^{(5)} + \frac{k\,Q''}{Q'} = (k + 2)^3.
					</me>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The first is <term>linear</term>: every term involving <m>w</m> or its
					derivatives has the form <m>a(t)\,w^{(n)}</m>&#8212;here <m>w^{(4)}</m>,
					<m>\frac{1}{t^3}w'</m>, and <m>9w</m>&#8212;while <m>\tan t</m> is a free
					term. Its coefficients being functions of <m>t</m> is fine.
				</p>
				<p>
					The second is <term>nonlinear</term>. The term <m>\frac{k\,Q''}{Q'}</m>
					has derivatives of the dependent variable <m>Q</m> in both the numerator
					and the denominator, so <m>Q''</m> and <m>Q'</m> are effectively
					multiplied/divided together. One offending term is enough: the whole
					equation is nonlinear. (Here <m>k</m> is a parameter, not the dependent
					variable, so <m>(k+2)^3</m> is just a free term.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Extension the book does not work out: classify modeling equations. -->
		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-modeling">
			<title>Looking past the book: classifying models</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Classification is the first thing we do to any model we meet later in
					the course. For each equation below, give its <em>order</em> and say
					whether it is <em>linear</em> or <em>nonlinear</em>. Assume the letter
					on the derivative is the dependent variable.
					<ol>
						<li><p>Skydiver with air resistance: <m>m\dfrac{dv}{dt} = mg - cv^2</m></p></li>
						<li><p>IV drug infusion: <m>\dfrac{dA}{dt} = r - kA</m></p></li>
						<li><p>RLC circuit charge: <m>L\dfrac{d^2 q}{dt^2} + R\dfrac{dq}{dt} + \dfrac{1}{C}q = E(t)</m></p></li>
						<li><p>Self-sustaining oscillator (van der Pol): <m>\dfrac{d^2 x}{dt^2} - \mu\left(1 - x^2\right)\dfrac{dx}{dt} + x = 0</m></p></li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<hint>
				<p>
					<m>m</m>, <m>g</m>, <m>c</m>, <m>r</m>, <m>k</m>, <m>L</m>, <m>R</m>,
					<m>C</m>, and <m>\mu</m> are constants (parameters), and <m>E(t)</m> is
					a known function of the independent variable&#8212;none of them is the
					dependent variable. Look only at how the dependent variable and its
					derivatives appear.
				</p>
			</hint>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<ol>
						<li><p><term>First-order, nonlinear.</term> Rewriting as <m>mv' + cv^2 = mg</m>, the <m>cv^2</m> term squares the dependent variable. (At low speeds drag is roughly proportional to <m>v</m> instead, which <em>linearizes</em> the model&#8212;a trade-off we will revisit.)</p></li>
						<li><p><term>First-order, linear.</term> It is <m>A' + kA = r</m>: one <m>a\,A'</m> term, one <m>a\,A</m> term, and a constant free term.</p></li>
						<li><p><term>Second-order, linear.</term> Each term is a constant times <m>q</m>, <m>q'</m>, or <m>q''</m>, and the forcing <m>E(t)</m> is a free term.</p></li>
						<li><p><term>Second-order, nonlinear.</term> The damping coefficient <m>-\mu(1 - x^2)</m> contains the dependent variable, so the middle term multiplies <m>x^2</m> by <m>x'</m>&#8212;coefficients are only allowed to involve the independent variable.</p></li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<title>Looking ahead</title>
			<p>
				Order and linearity are the two labels we will read off <em>first</em>
				for every new equation, because together they decide which technique to
				reach for. Next we turn to what it even means to <em>solve</em> a
				differential equation&#8212;how to check that a candidate function really
				satisfies the equation, and how an initial condition pins down the one
				solution we want out of the whole family.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>
</worksheet>
